        output='Based on the provided financial disclosures, here is a breakdown of the Connectivity segment\'s revenue and a definition of its components.\n\n### Connectivity Segment Revenue Breakdown (Consumer vs. Enterprise & Government)\n\nYes, the Connectivity segment\'s revenue is broken down between **Consumer Starlink revenue** and **Enterprise & Government revenue**. The primary source for this breakdown is the disaggregated revenue table.\n\nFor the fiscal year ended December 31, 2025, the split was as follows:\n\n| Revenue Line Item | Amount (2025) | Description |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Consumer** | $7,208 million | Revenue from individual and residential Starlink subscribers. |\n| **Enterprise & Government** | $4,179 million | Revenue from business and public-sector customers, **which includes Starlink Mobile service offerings.** |\n| **Total Connectivity** | **$11,387 million** | Sum of Consumer and Enterprise & Government revenue. |\n\n**Growth Drivers (as per MD&A):**\n*   **Consumer revenue** growth is driven by increases in the number of Starlink subscribers, partially offset by a declining Average Revenue Per User (ARPU) due to international expansion and lower-priced plans.\n*   **Enterprise & Government revenue** growth is driven by the expansion of aviation, maritime, mobility, and other enterprise businesses, as well as government connectivity contracts (Starshield).\n\n---\n\n### Definition: Components of the Connectivity Segment\n\nThe Connectivity segment encompasses the **Starlink business**, generating revenue from two primary sources: **services** and **products**.\n\n**1. Services:**\n*   **Consumer Broadband:** Monthly subscription fees for high-speed internet access, priced by geography and speed. Revenue is recognized ratably over the subscription period (month-to-month).\n*   **Enterprise & Government Connectivity:** A mix of contract structures:\n    *   **Subscriptions & Data Usage:** Similar to consumer plans but often with customized terms and SLAs.\n    *   **Capacity Contracts:** Agreements for dedicated network capacity.\n    *   **Starshield:** Long-term, multi-year contracts for a secure government satellite network. Revenue for these is recognized **over time using the cost-to-cost input method** (percentage-of-completion).\n*   **Starlink Mobile:** Revenue from satellite-to-mobile services (texting, voice, data) provided through **revenue-sharing arrangements with Mobile Network Operator (MNO) partners**.\n\n**2. Products:**\n*   **Starlink Kit Sales:** One-time revenue from the sale of hardware kits (including the satellite terminal). Revenue is recognized **upon delivery to the customer** (or upon installation for certain enterprise customers), net of returns and allowances. The disclosure notes state, "All of products revenue is attributable to the Connectivity segment."\n\n**In summary,** the Connectivity segment is the company\'s **satellite-based internet service provider (Starlink)**, offering broadband and mobile connectivity services to consumers, businesses, and governments worldwide, along with the associated hardware kits needed to access the service.',
